  <div class="section-label">Approach</div>
  <h2 class="content-h">How I Built It</h2>
  <div class="content-body">
    <p><strong>Step 1: Data Audit &amp; Modeling</strong></p>
    <p>I started by auditing all 6 existing Excel files to understand the data structure, relationships, and gaps. From there, I designed a proper star schema in SQL Server — a central fact table for orders, surrounded by dimension tables for products, customers, dates, and sales channels.</p>
    <p><strong>Step 2: ETL with Python</strong></p>
    <p>I wrote Python scripts using Pandas to automate the extraction, cleaning, and loading of daily order data from their order management system into SQL Server. This eliminated the manual export/import process entirely.</p>
    <p><strong>Step 3: Power BI Development</strong></p>
    <p>The dashboard was built in Power BI with DAX measures for all KPIs. Key pages included:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Executive Summary — revenue, orders, AOV, and YoY comparisons</li>
      <li>Product Performance — sales by category, top/bottom performers, margin analysis</li>
      <li>Customer Analytics — new vs returning, geographic breakdown, LTV cohorts</li>
      <li>Trend Analysis — daily/weekly/monthly revenue with rolling averages</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Step 4: Deployment &amp; Training</strong></p>
    <p>The dashboard was published to Power BI Service with row-level security for different team roles. I delivered a 90-minute training session and a written guide for the team.</p>
  </div>

